Previous abstract:
\begin{abstract}
The transport of passive tracers in two-dimensional chaotic flows governed by point-vortex dynamics often exhibits anomalous superdiffusion, yet its precise statistical connection to canonical models like Lévy walks remains unclear. Here, we investigate this connection by numerically simulating tracer trajectories in Hamiltonian point-vortex systems with a varying number of vortices, $N$, and comparing their statistical properties to a synthetic dataset of Lévy walks. Through a comprehensive analysis of the mean squared displacement (MSD), velocity autocorrelation, residence time distributions, and displacement probability density functions, we demonstrate a systematic transition from near-normal diffusion (MSD exponent $\alpha \approx 1.05$) for low vortex numbers ($N=5$) to strong superdiffusion ($\alpha \approx 1.52$) for high vortex numbers ($N=40$). This transition is mechanistically linked to the emergence of power-law tails in the residence time distributions, indicative of Lévy-like trapping, and the development of non-Gaussian, heavy-tailed displacement distributions that quantitatively match a comparable Lévy walk model. Despite these similarities, we identify a crucial difference in their long-time statistical properties: the vortex systems become progressively more ergodic as superdiffusion strengthens with increasing $N$, a trend opposite to that observed in canonical Lévy walks. This finding, quantified by an ergodicity-breaking parameter, highlights the distinct role of the underlying Hamiltonian chaos in shaping the transport dynamics compared to stochastic models.
\end{abstract}

