\subsection{Evolution of displacement distributions}

We further examined the one-dimensional displacement probability density functions (PDFs), $P(\Delta x)$, for the most superdiffusive cases: the $N=40$ vortex system and the $\beta=1.5$ Lévy walk. Figure \ref{fig:pdfs} shows the evolution of these PDFs with increasing lag time $\Delta t$.

For both systems, the PDFs are nearly Gaussian at very short lag times. As $\Delta t$ increases, the distributions develop heavy, non-Gaussian tails. At the longest lag times shown, the core of the distributions remains approximately Gaussian, but the tails decay much slower, consistent with a Lévy-stable distribution. This convergence towards a non-Gaussian attractor for the displacement statistics provides further strong evidence that, from a kinematic perspective, the chaotic vortex flow effectively reproduces the statistical signatures of a Lévy process. The primary difference observed is that the heavy tails develop more rapidly for the Lévy walk, which is expected since long flights are a fundamental component of the process, whereas in the vortex system they are an emergent property of the chaotic advection.

